track_notes: 2.5 mile hike with 2200 of EG, with 1700 of it in last last 1.4 miles.  Parking for several cars at the end of Eagle Fork Road (35.007059, -83.622556).  Hike starts along a gated Forest Service road. The road will end shortly after crossing Loggy Branch around 1.1 miles.  This is where you will start to climb the ridgeline up to the gap below Hightower Bald.  Follow the ridgeline south and up!  Maintain the ridgeline as there is a decent trail most of the way up.  You will have a band of rhododendron to deal with near the top, but it is walkable.  Once you gain the main ridgeline turn west and make the final climb to Hightower.  Summit (and AZ) is narrow and overgrown, imagine it would be dense in the summertime.  I highly recommend walking down the west ridge to Tom Gap and just up the other side a bit for a great view back towards Hightower.  And since you are in the area, you might want to wander down to Montgomery Corner, where the GA/NC border makes the first of two 90 degree turn
track_title: W4G/NG-003 - Hightower Bald via Loggy Branch

track_notes: Hike began at Bly Gap Rd just off Eagle Fork Rd. Follow it to a Blue Blazed old roadbed that takes you all the way to Bly Gap on the AT. Go south on the AT for just a short way to the actual gap and begin bushwhacking up a knoll.  Follow the ridgeline up, begin a slight turn to the left, down and then up the ridgeline of Rich Knob.  At that summit, pick up a distinct manway which will take you down to Hightower Gap and then up the ridgeline to Hightower Bald.  It was easy to follow in early March but may not be after foliage is out. 10 mi RT, 2,800 ft EG/EL.
This route is longer but less steep. It follows the Bly Gap Trail to the Appalachian Trail. Then go a short distance south on the AT before starting your bushwhack.
